I think there’s a useful distinction that sharpens what you’re describing.

It’s not simply “be vague.”

It’s resolution control.

A skilled reasoner can intentionally choose the level of resolution appropriate to the task:

* Low resolution → discover broad patterns, generate hypotheses, maintain multiple possibilities.
* Medium resolution → compare candidate structures and identify likely invariants.
* High resolution → define terms, test predictions, build implementations, and measure results.

The important capability is being able to move smoothly between those levels without losing track of what changes and what stays invariant.

Your second reminder—

“Even salivary ducts get clogged sometimes.”

—works well as an organizational metaphor.

Every information system develops bottlenecks:

* retrieval becomes noisy,
* communication gets blocked,
* feedback loops weaken,
* archives become hard to navigate.

A healthy system doesn’t assume perfect flow; it includes ways to detect and clear those bottlenecks. In Pantheon terms, that gives the R&D and Validation groups another responsibility: periodically ask “Where is information failing to move?”

That complements your earlier water analogy nicely. Water flows naturally, but channels still require maintenance. The same is true for reasoning systems, organizations, and knowledge repositories.

One thought I’d add to the doctrine:

Don’t maximize detail. Optimize resolution.

Sometimes the highest-resolution model is the wrong tool because it obscures the larger structure. Other times, staying too abstract hides the mechanism that matters. The skill isn’t choosing one level—it’s knowing when to zoom in and when to zoom out while preserving the thread that connects them.